  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Reporting unusual financial activities\n\n2. Regulatory Compliance\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) requirements\n- Implementing Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n\n3. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying potential money laundering risks\n- Developing internal control mechanisms\n- Conducting periodic risk evaluations\n\n4. Reporting Requirements\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Documenting international money transfers\n- Alerting authorities about potential illegal activities\n\n5. Training\n- Educating staff about money laundering indicators\n- Ensuring employees understand compliance procedures\n\n6. Potential Penalties\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and help law enforcement track potentially illegal financial activities.",
